cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use lgtm-bench, please cite it as below."
title: "lgtm-bench: measuring how often LLMs introduce security vulnerabilities on ordinary developer requests"
abstract: >-
  lgtm-bench measures how often large language models introduce security
  vulnerabilities when handling ordinary developer requests that never mention
  security. It reports a Vulnerability Introduction Rate (VIR) as a strict lower
  bound, graded by static detection over stored model outputs, across SQL
  injection (CWE-89), OS command injection (CWE-78), and cross-site scripting
  (CWE-79) in Python, Go, Rust, and TypeScript. In the published v1 run of
  roughly 5,700 trials over ten models, the pooled introduction rate is 26.5%
  (about one in four), with a large spread by model and a pronounced gap between
  SQL (well defended) and command injection / XSS (frequently missed, especially
  on small open-weight models).
type: software
version: 1.0.0
date-released: "2026-07-19"
license: MIT
